\begin{document}

\title{Applying the Onsager Discrete Method to a Tumor Growth Model}

%\author{Weijie Huang}
%\affiliation{School of Mathematics and Statistics, Beijing Jiaotong University, Beijing 100044, China}
%\email{wjhuang@bjtu.edu.cn}
%
%\author{Xinran Ruan}
%\affiliation{School of Mathematical Sciences, Capital Normal University, Beijing 100048, China}
%\email{xinran.ruan@cun.edu.cn}

\date{}
\maketitle

\begin{abstract}
We propose a structure-preserving numerical method for a pressure-driven
tumor growth model with pressure-dependent proliferation. The model is a
degenerate porous-medium type equation with pressure law \(p=n^\gamma\),
and it approaches a Hele--Shaw type free boundary problem in the stiff
pressure limit. The method is derived from the Onsager variational
principle. By introducing a modified energy shifted by the homeostatic
pressure, the growth term can be written in a dissipative form and treated
together with the transport part in a unified Rayleighian formulation.
This leads to a time-discrete constrained minimization problem and a fully
discrete finite difference scheme with explicit mobilities and an implicit
pressure update. We prove that the scheme preserves nonnegativity, the
homeostatic upper bound, and a discrete modified energy dissipation law.
Numerical experiments in one and two space dimensions demonstrate the
accuracy and robustness of the method. The scheme captures Barenblatt
solutions, preserves mass and energy dissipation in the pure diffusion
case, remains stable for nonzero growth, and reproduces the convergence
toward the Hele--Shaw limit for large \(\gamma\). Two-dimensional examples
further show its ability to resolve free boundary evolutions with topology
changes.
\end{abstract}


\section{Introduction}

Mathematical models for tumor growth provide an important framework for
understanding the interaction between cell proliferation, mechanical pressure,
and free boundary motion. In many continuum descriptions, the tumor cell
population is represented by a density variable, and the mechanical response of
the tissue is described through a pressure law. A widely used class of models is
given by porous-medium type equations with pressure-dependent proliferation.
Such models are able to describe finite-speed propagation of the tumor region
and lead, in the stiff-pressure limit, to Hele--Shaw type free boundary
problems. These features make them useful both for mathematical analysis and
for numerical simulation of tumor growth phenomena.

In this paper, we consider the pressure-driven tumor growth model
\begin{equation}\label{eq:tumor-model}
\partial_t n+\nabla\cdot j=nG(p),\qquad
j=-n\nabla p,\qquad
p=n^\gamma ,
\end{equation}
posed in a bounded domain \(\Omega\subset\mathbb R^d\). Here
\(n=n(x,t)\ge 0\) denotes the tumor cell density, \(j=j(x,t)\) is the cell
flux, \(p=p(x,t)\) is the mechanical pressure, and \(\gamma>1\) is the
stiffness parameter in the pressure law. The function \(G\) represents the net
proliferation rate. It is usually assumed that cell growth is inhibited by
large pressure and vanishes at a homeostatic pressure. The precise structural
assumptions on \(G\) will be stated in Section~\ref{sec:model}.

The model \eqref{eq:intro-model} has attracted considerable attention in the
analysis of tumor growth and free boundary limits. For fixed \(\gamma\), it is a
degenerate reaction-diffusion equation. When \(\gamma\) becomes large, the
density tends to satisfy a congestion constraint, while the pressure becomes a
Lagrange multiplier associated with the saturated region. The limiting problem
is closely related to a Hele--Shaw free boundary problem with growth. This
singular limit is important for tumor growth modeling, since it connects
compressible density-based descriptions with incompressible free boundary
models.

From the numerical point of view, the model contains several difficulties. The
diffusion is degenerate in vacuum regions, and the solution may develop sharp
interfaces. The growth term changes the total mass and must be treated in a way
that is compatible with the pressure inhibition mechanism. In addition, when
\(\gamma\) is large, the pressure law becomes stiff, and a numerical method
should remain robust without requiring excessive mesh refinement or very small
time steps. It is therefore desirable to construct schemes that preserve the
main structural properties of the continuous model, including nonnegativity,
upper bounds, energy dissipation, and the correct incompressible-limit
behavior.

The purpose of this paper is to develop a structure-preserving numerical method
for \eqref{eq:intro-model} based on the Onsager variational principle. The key
observation is that, after shifting the pressure energy by the homeostatic
pressure, the pressure-dependent growth term can be written in a dissipative
form. This allows us to incorporate both the transport part and the reaction
part into a unified Onsager formulation. Based on this formulation, we construct
a discrete Rayleighian and derive a time-discrete scheme through a constrained
minimization problem. The resulting scheme naturally inherits a modified energy
dissipation law.

The main contributions of this paper are summarized as follows. First, we give
an Onsager variational formulation for the pressure-driven tumor growth model
with pressure-inhibited proliferation. Both the transport flux and the reaction
source are obtained from the minimization of a Rayleighian functional. Second,
we propose a time-discrete scheme based on a discrete Rayleighian formulation
and prove its energy stability. Third, we present a fully discrete finite
difference scheme and show that it preserves nonnegativity, the homeostatic
upper bound, and a discrete modified energy dissipation law. Fourth, we study
the asymptotic-preserving property of the fully discrete scheme in the limit
\(\gamma\to\infty\). Finally, we provide numerical experiments in one and two
space dimensions to verify the accuracy, structure preservation, large-\(\gamma\)
behavior, and robustness of the proposed method for free boundary evolutions.

The rest of the paper is organized as follows. In Section~\ref{sec:model}, we
present the model, state the assumptions on the growth function, and collect
several structural properties. In Section~\ref{sec:onsager}, we derive the
Onsager formulation and construct the time-discrete scheme. In
Section~\ref{sec:fully-discrete}, we introduce the fully discrete finite
difference scheme and prove its structure-preserving properties. In
Section~\ref{sec:ap}, we analyze the asymptotic-preserving property in the
incompressible limit. Numerical experiments are reported in
Section~\ref{sec:numerics}. Finally, conclusions are given in
Section~\ref{sec:conclusion}.

\section{The model and its structural properties}\label{sec:model}
In this section, we fix the setting and assumptions for the model
\eqref{eq:tumor-model}. We also recall several elementary estimates for
smooth solutions.

Let \(\Omega\subset\mathbb R^d\) be a bounded domain. Throughout this
section, \(n=n(x,t)\), \(j=j(x,t)\), and \(p=p(x,t)\) are as in
\eqref{eq:tumor-model}, and the equations are considered in
\(\Omega\times(0,T]\). The initial condition is
\begin{equation}\label{eq:initial-condition}
    n(x,0)=n_0(x),
    \qquad x\in\Omega .
\end{equation}
The corresponding initial pressure is
\[
    p_0(x)=p(x,0)=n_0(x)^\gamma .
\]
On the boundary, we impose the no-flux condition
\begin{equation}\label{eq:no-flux}
    j\cdot\nu=0,
    \qquad x\in\partial\Omega,\quad 0<t\le T ,
\end{equation}
where \(\nu\) denotes the outward unit normal vector.

For the growth function \(G\) in \eqref{eq:tumor-model}, we assume that
there exists a homeostatic pressure \(p_H>0\) such that
\(G\in C^1([0,\infty))\) and
\begin{equation}\label{eq:g-assumption}
G(p_H)=0,
\qquad
G'(p)\le 0,
\qquad p\ge 0 .
\end{equation}
This assumption is commonly used in mechanical tumor growth models
\cite{} and means that the growth rate decreases as the pressure increases
and vanishes at \(p=p_H\). It immediately gives
\begin{equation}\label{eq:g-dissipative}
(p-p_H)G(p)\le0,
\qquad p\ge0 .
\end{equation}

With this assumption, the following elementary estimates hold for smooth
solutions.
\begin{proposition}[Positivity, upper bound, and mass estimate]
\label{prop:continuous-bounds}
Assume that \(n_0\ge0\) in \(\Omega\). Then any smooth solution of
\eqref{eq:tumor-model} subject to \eqref{eq:initial-condition} and
\eqref{eq:no-flux} satisfies
\[
    n(x,t)\ge0,
    \qquad
    p(x,t)\ge0,
    \qquad x\in\Omega,\quad 0\le t\le T .
\]
If, in addition, \(0\le p_0\le p_H\) in \(\Omega\), then
\begin{equation}\label{eq:continuous-upper-bound}
    0\le p(x,t)\le p_H,
    \qquad
    0\le n(x,t)\le n_H:=p_H^{1/\gamma},
    \qquad x\in\Omega,\quad 0\le t\le T .
\end{equation}
Moreover,
\begin{equation}\label{eq:l1-bound-property}
    \int_\Omega n(x,t)\,dx
    \le
    e^{G(0)t}\int_\Omega n_0(x)\,dx,
    \qquad 0\le t\le T .
\end{equation}
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}
The nonnegativity follows formally from the comparison principle. Indeed,
\(n=0\) is an invariant state of the equation, since both the flux and the
reaction term vanish when \(n=0\). Hence nonnegative initial data remain
nonnegative. Since \(p=n^\gamma\), this also gives \(p\ge0\).

We next prove the upper bound. Differentiating the pressure law
\(p=n^\gamma\) in time and using \eqref{eq:tumor-model}, we obtain the
pressure equation
\begin{equation}\label{eq:pressure-equation-property}
    \partial_t p
    =
    |\nabla p|^2+\gamma p\bigl(\Delta p+G(p)\bigr).
\end{equation}
The constant function \(p_H\) is a supersolution of
\eqref{eq:pressure-equation-property}, since \(G(p_H)=0\). To see this,
suppose that \(p\) reaches \(p_H\) from below for the first time. At a
maximum point, the maximum principle gives \(\nabla p=0\) and
\(\Delta p\le0\). Thus, by \eqref{eq:pressure-equation-property},
\[
    \partial_t p
    =
    \gamma p_H\Delta p+\gamma p_HG(p_H)
    \le0 .
\]
Therefore \(p\) cannot cross \(p_H\), and hence \(p\le p_H\). The bound
for \(n\) follows from \(p=n^\gamma\).

It remains to prove the mass estimate. Integrating \eqref{eq:tumor-model}
over \(\Omega\) and using the no-flux condition \eqref{eq:no-flux}, we get
\[
    \frac{d}{dt}\int_\Omega n\,dx
    =
    \int_\Omega nG(p)\,dx .
\]
Since \(p\ge0\) and \(G\) is nonincreasing, \(G(p)\le G(0)\). Together
with \(n\ge0\), this gives
\[
    \frac{d}{dt}\int_\Omega n\,dx
    \le
    G(0)\int_\Omega n\,dx .
\]
The estimate \eqref{eq:l1-bound-property} follows from Gronwall's
inequality.
\end{proof}


\begin{proposition}[Modified energy dissipation]
\label{prop:energy-dissipation}
Define the modified energy by
\begin{equation}\label{eq:modified-energy}
    \mathcal E(n)
    =
    \int_\Omega
    \left(
    \frac{1}{\gamma+1}n^{\gamma+1}-p_H n
    \right)\,dx .
\end{equation}
Let \(n\) be a nonnegative smooth solution of \eqref{eq:tumor-model}
subject to the no-flux boundary condition \eqref{eq:no-flux}. Then
\begin{equation}\label{eq:modified-energy-balance}
    \frac{d}{dt}\mathcal E(n)
    =
    -\int_\Omega n|\nabla p|^2\,dx
    +
    \int_\Omega n(p-p_H)G(p)\,dx .
\end{equation}
Consequently, by \eqref{eq:g-dissipative},
\begin{equation}\label{eq:modified-energy-dissipation}
    \frac{d}{dt}\mathcal E(n)
    \le
    -\int_\Omega n|\nabla p|^2\,dx
    \le0 .
\end{equation}
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}
Since
\[
    \frac{\delta\mathcal E}{\delta n}
    =
    n^\gamma-p_H
    =
    p-p_H ,
\]
using \eqref{eq:tumor-model} gives
\begin{align*}
    \frac{d}{dt}\mathcal E(n)
    &=
    \int_\Omega (p-p_H)\partial_t n\,dx  \\
    &=
    \int_\Omega (p-p_H)
    \left(\nabla\cdot(n\nabla p)+nG(p)\right)\,dx  \\
    &=
    -\int_\Omega n\nabla p\cdot\nabla(p-p_H)\,dx
    +
    \int_\Omega n(p-p_H)G(p)\,dx  \\
    &=
    -\int_\Omega n|\nabla p|^2\,dx
    +
    \int_\Omega n(p-p_H)G(p)\,dx .
\end{align*}
Here the boundary term vanishes because
\(n\nabla p\cdot\nu=-j\cdot\nu=0\) on \(\partial\Omega\). This proves
\eqref{eq:modified-energy-balance}. Since \(n\ge0\), the second term on
the right-hand side is nonpositive by \eqref{eq:g-dissipative}. Hence
\eqref{eq:modified-energy-dissipation} follows.
\end{proof}

\begin{remark}\label{rem:modified-energy}
The first term in \eqref{eq:modified-energy} is the usual energy associated
with the pressure law. The additional linear term \(-p_Hn\) shifts the
variational derivative from \(p\) to \(p-p_H\). Since the gradient is
unchanged, this shift does not affect the transport part. Its effect appears
only in the reaction contribution, where the factor \(p-p_H\) gives the sign
in \eqref{eq:modified-energy-balance} through \eqref{eq:g-dissipative}. This
shifted variational derivative will be used in the Onsager formulation below.
\end{remark}



%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%


\section{Onsager formulation and numerical scheme}
\label{sec:onsager-scheme}

We now derive the numerical scheme from the Onsager variational principle \cite{}.
We first introduce the continuous Rayleighian and show that its
Euler--Lagrange equations recover the model \eqref{eq:tumor-model}. The
time-discrete scheme is then obtained from a time-discrete Rayleighian.
Finally, we give the fully discrete finite difference formulation.
\subsection{Onsager variational formulation}
\label{subsec:onsager-formulation}

We begin with the continuous Onsager formulation of
\eqref{eq:tumor-model}. Let \(\mathcal E\) be the modified energy defined
in \eqref{eq:modified-energy}. We set
\begin{equation}\label{eq:modified-chemical-potential}
    \mu
    :=
    \frac{\delta\mathcal E}{\delta n}
    =
    p-p_H ,
\end{equation}
and use \(\mu\) as the chemical potential in what follows.


To separate transport and reaction, introduce a reaction rate \(r\) and
write the density equation as
\begin{equation}\label{eq:balance-with-r}
    \partial_t n+\nabla\cdot j=r .
\end{equation}
This balance law will be used as the constraint in the Onsager
minimization.


For later use, we introduce the reaction mobility
\begin{equation}\label{eq:reaction-mobility}
    \mathcal M(n,p)
    =
    \begin{cases}
    -\dfrac{nG(p)}{p-p_H}, & p\ne p_H,\\[1.2ex]
    -nG'(p_H), & p=p_H .
    \end{cases}
\end{equation}
The second value is the limit of the first one as \(p\to p_H\), using
\(G(p_H)=0\). By \eqref{eq:g-assumption} and
\eqref{eq:g-dissipative}, \(\mathcal M(n,p)\ge0\) for \(n\ge0\) and
\(p\ge0\). 


With the transport mobility \(n\) and the reaction mobility
\(\mathcal M(n,p)\), we define the dissipation functional
\begin{equation}\label{eq:total-dissipation}
    \Phi(n;j,r)
    =
    \frac12\int_\Omega \frac{|j|^2}{n}\,dx
    +
    \frac12\int_\Omega \frac{r^2}{\mathcal M(n,p)}\,dx .
\end{equation}
Since
\[
    \frac{d}{dt}\mathcal E(n)
    =
    \int_\Omega \mu\,\partial_t n\,dx ,
\]
the Rayleighian is defined by
\begin{equation}\label{eq:rayleighian}
    \mathcal R(n;\partial_t n,j,r)
    =
    \Phi(n;j,r)
    +
    \frac{d}{dt}\mathcal E(n)
    =
    \int_\Omega
    \left(
    \frac{|j|^2}{2n}
    +
    \frac{r^2}{2\mathcal M(n,p)}
    +
    \mu\,\partial_t n
    \right)dx .
\end{equation}

For a fixed density \(n\), the quantities \(p\), \(\mu\), and
\(\mathcal M(n,p)\) are regarded as given. According to the Onsager
principle, the rate variables \(\partial_t n\), \(j\), and \(r\) are
determined by minimizing \(\mathcal R\) under the constraint
\eqref{eq:balance-with-r}. Introducing a Lagrange multiplier \(\lambda\),
define
\begin{equation}\label{eq:augmented-rayleighian}
    \mathcal R_\lambda
    =
    \mathcal R
    -
    \int_\Omega
    \lambda\left(\partial_t n+\nabla\cdot j-r\right)dx .
\end{equation}
Setting the first variation of \(\mathcal R_\lambda\) to zero with respect
to \(\partial_t n\), \(j\), \(r\), and \(\lambda\), respectively, gives
\begin{align}
    &\mu-\lambda=0,
    \label{eq:variation-nt}\\
    &\frac{j}{n}+\nabla\lambda=0,
    \label{eq:variation-j}\\
    &\frac{r}{\mathcal M(n,p)}+\lambda=0,
    \label{eq:variation-r}\\
    &\partial_t n+\nabla\cdot j=r .
    \label{eq:variation-lambda}
\end{align}
In deriving \eqref{eq:variation-j}, the boundary term from integration by
parts vanishes under the no-flux condition \eqref{eq:no-flux}.

From \eqref{eq:variation-nt}, we have \(\lambda=\mu\). Then
\eqref{eq:variation-j}, together with
\eqref{eq:modified-chemical-potential}, gives
\[
    j
    =
    -n\nabla\lambda
    =
    -n\nabla\mu
    =
    -n\nabla p .
\]
Similarly, using \eqref{eq:variation-r},
\eqref{eq:modified-chemical-potential}, and
\eqref{eq:reaction-mobility}, we obtain
\[
    r
    =
    -\mathcal M(n,p)\lambda
    =
    -\mathcal M(n,p)\mu
    =
    nG(p).
\]
Substituting these two relations into the balance law
\eqref{eq:balance-with-r}, and recalling \(p=n^\gamma\), we recover
\eqref{eq:tumor-model}.


\begin{remark}[Pure diffusion case]\label{rem:onsager-pure-diffusion}
When \(G\equiv0\), the reaction term is absent. In this case, the reaction
rate \(r\) and the reaction dissipation term in \eqref{eq:total-dissipation}
are omitted. The balance law reduces to
\[
    \partial_t n+\nabla\cdot j=0,
\]
and the Rayleighian becomes
\[
    \mathcal R(n;\partial_t n,j)
    =
    \int_\Omega
    \left(
    \frac{|j|^2}{2n}
    +
    \mu\,\partial_t n
    \right)dx .
\]
Minimization under the above mass balance gives
\[
    j=-n\nabla\mu=-n\nabla p.
\]
Together with \(p=n^\gamma\), this recovers the pure porous medium
equation.
\end{remark}

\subsection{Time-discrete scheme from a discrete Rayleighian}
\label{subsec:time-discrete}

We next derive a time-discrete scheme from the Rayleighian formulation.
Let \(\tau>0\) be the time step and \(t_k=k\tau\). Suppose that
\(n^k\) is known, and set
\[
    p^k=(n^k)^\gamma .
\]
The mobilities in the dissipation terms are evaluated at the known state
\(n^k\). Thus the transport mobility is \(n^k\), and the reaction mobility
is given pointwise by
\begin{equation}\label{eq:discrete-reaction-mobility}
    \mathcal M^k
    =
    \begin{cases}
    -\dfrac{n^kG(p^k)}{p^k-p_H}, & p^k\ne p_H,\\[1.2ex]
    -n^kG'(p_H), & p^k=p_H .
    \end{cases}
\end{equation}
As before, the second value is the limiting value at \(p^k=p_H\). From
\eqref{eq:g-assumption} and \eqref{eq:g-dissipative}, we have
\[
    \mathcal M^k\ge0
    \qquad \text{if } n^k\ge0 .
\]

For trial variables \(n\), \(j\), and \(r\), we discretize the balance law
\eqref{eq:balance-with-r} over one time step as
\begin{equation}\label{eq:time-discrete-balance-jr}
    \frac{n-n^k}{\tau}+\nabla\cdot j=r,
    \qquad
    j\cdot\nu=0
    \quad \text{on }\partial\Omega .
\end{equation}
The time-discrete Rayleighian is defined by
\begin{equation}\label{eq:time-discrete-rayleighian}
    \mathcal R_\tau^k(n,j,r)
    =
    \frac{\mathcal E(n)-\mathcal E(n^k)}{\tau}
    +
    \frac12\int_\Omega \frac{|j|^2}{n^k}\,dx
    +
    \frac12\int_\Omega \frac{r^2}{\mathcal M^k}\,dx .
\end{equation}

Introducing
\[
    m=\tau j,
    \qquad
    q=\tau r,
\]
we can rewrite \eqref{eq:time-discrete-balance-jr} as
\begin{equation}\label{eq:discrete-balance}
    n-n^k+\nabla\cdot m=q,
    \qquad
    m\cdot\nu=0
    \quad \text{on }\partial\Omega .
\end{equation}

After multiplying \eqref{eq:time-discrete-rayleighian} by \(\tau\) and
dropping the constant \(\mathcal E(n^k)\), the minimization of
\(\mathcal R_\tau^k\) is equivalent to the minimization of
\begin{equation}\label{eq:discrete-rayleighian}
    \mathcal J_\tau^k(n,m,q)
    =
    \mathcal E(n)
    +
    \frac{1}{2\tau}\int_\Omega \frac{|m|^2}{n^k}\,dx
    +
    \frac{1}{2\tau}\int_\Omega \frac{q^2}{\mathcal M^k}\,dx .
\end{equation}

The next time step is defined by
\begin{equation}\label{eq:discrete-minimization}
    (n^{k+1},m^{k+1},q^{k+1})
    =
    \operatorname*{arg\,min}_{(n,m,q)\in\mathcal A^k}
    \mathcal J_\tau^k(n,m,q),
\end{equation}
where the admissible set is
\begin{equation}\label{eq:admissible-set}
    \mathcal A^k
    =
    \left\{
    (n,m,q)\ \middle|\
    n\ge0,\quad
    n-n^k+\nabla\cdot m=q \ \text{in }\Omega,\quad
    m\cdot\nu=0 \ \text{on }\partial\Omega
    \right\}.
\end{equation}

We now derive the Euler--Lagrange equations of the constrained
minimization problem \eqref{eq:discrete-minimization}. Introducing a
Lagrange multiplier \(\lambda\) for the constraint
\eqref{eq:discrete-balance}, define
\[
    \mathcal J_{\tau,\lambda}^k
    =
    \mathcal J_\tau^k
    -
    \int_\Omega
    \lambda\left(n-n^k+\nabla\cdot m-q\right)\,dx .
\]
Let \((n^{k+1},m^{k+1},q^{k+1})\) be a smooth minimizer, and denote the
corresponding multiplier by \(\lambda^{k+1}\). Setting the first variation
of \(\mathcal J_{\tau,\lambda}^k\) to zero with respect to \(n\), \(m\),
\(q\), and \(\lambda\), respectively, gives
\begin{align}
    &\frac{\delta\mathcal E}{\delta n}(n^{k+1})
    -\lambda^{k+1}=0,
    \label{eq:el-discrete-n}\\
    &\frac{m^{k+1}}{\tau n^k}
    +\nabla\lambda^{k+1}=0,
    \label{eq:el-discrete-m}\\
    &\frac{q^{k+1}}{\tau\mathcal M^k}
    +\lambda^{k+1}=0,
    \label{eq:el-discrete-q}\\
    &n^{k+1}-n^k+\nabla\cdot m^{k+1}=q^{k+1}.
    \label{eq:el-discrete-constraint}
\end{align}
In deriving \eqref{eq:el-discrete-m}, the boundary term from integration by
parts vanishes under the boundary condition in \eqref{eq:discrete-balance}.

From \eqref{eq:el-discrete-n}, we have
\[
    \lambda^{k+1}
    =
    \mu^{k+1}
    :=
    p^{k+1}-p_H,
    \qquad
    p^{k+1}=(n^{k+1})^\gamma .
\]
Then \eqref{eq:el-discrete-m} and \eqref{eq:el-discrete-q} give
\begin{equation}\label{eq:time-discrete-flux-reaction}
\begin{aligned}
    m^{k+1}
    &=
    -\tau n^k\nabla\lambda^{k+1}
    =
    -\tau n^k\nabla\mu^{k+1},\\
    q^{k+1}
    &=
    -\tau\mathcal M^k\lambda^{k+1}
    =
    -\tau\mathcal M^k\mu^{k+1}.
\end{aligned}
\end{equation}
Substituting \eqref{eq:time-discrete-flux-reaction} into
\eqref{eq:el-discrete-constraint} gives
\begin{equation}\label{eq:time-discrete-scheme}
    \frac{n^{k+1}-n^k}{\tau}
    =
    \nabla\cdot\left(n^k\nabla\mu^{k+1}\right)
    -
    \mathcal M^k\mu^{k+1},
    \qquad
    \mu^{k+1}=p^{k+1}-p_H .
\end{equation}
Since \(\nabla\mu^{k+1}=\nabla p^{k+1}\), this is equivalently written as
\begin{equation}\label{eq:time-discrete-scheme-pressure}
    \frac{n^{k+1}-n^k}{\tau}
    =
    \nabla\cdot\left(n^k\nabla p^{k+1}\right)
    -
    \mathcal M^k\left(p^{k+1}-p_H\right),
    \qquad
    p^{k+1}=(n^{k+1})^\gamma .
\end{equation} 
The boundary condition follows from \(m^{k+1}\cdot\nu=0\) in
\eqref{eq:discrete-balance}. Using the first relation in
\eqref{eq:time-discrete-flux-reaction} and
\(\nabla\mu^{k+1}=\nabla p^{k+1}\), we obtain
\begin{equation}\label{eq:time-discrete-boundary}
    n^k\nabla p^{k+1}\cdot\nu=0
    \qquad \text{on }\partial\Omega .
\end{equation}

Before passing to the spatial discretization, we record the bound-preserving
property and the energy stability of the time-discrete scheme.


\begin{proposition}[Positivity and upper bound]
\label{prop:td-positivity-upper-bound}
Assume that \(n^k\ge0\). Let
\((n^{k+1},m^{k+1},q^{k+1})\) be a minimizer of
\eqref{eq:discrete-minimization}. Then
\[
    n^{k+1}\ge0 .
\]
If, in addition, \(0\le n^k\le n_H\), assume that this minimizer is smooth
and satisfies the Euler--Lagrange system
\eqref{eq:time-discrete-scheme-pressure} and
\eqref{eq:time-discrete-boundary}. Then
\[
    0\le n^{k+1}\le n_H,
    \qquad
    0\le p^{k+1}\le p_H .
\]
\end{proposition}


\begin{proof}\color{red}{...}
The nonnegativity follows from the definition of the admissible set
\eqref{eq:admissible-set}, which requires \(n\ge0\).


We prove the upper bound. Set
\[
    w=(p^{k+1}-p_H)_+ .
\]
Since \(p^{k+1}=(n^{k+1})^\gamma\), on the set where \(w>0\) we have
\(p^{k+1}>p_H\), and hence \(n^{k+1}>n_H\). Using the assumption
\(n^k\le n_H\), this gives
\[
    (n^{k+1}-n^k)w\ge0
    \qquad \text{in }\Omega .
\]

Multiplying \eqref{eq:time-discrete-scheme-pressure} by \(w\), integrating
over \(\Omega\), and using the boundary condition
\eqref{eq:time-discrete-boundary}, we obtain
\[
    \frac1\tau\int_\Omega (n^{k+1}-n^k)w\,dx
    =
    -\int_\Omega n^k|\nabla w|^2\,dx
    -
    \int_\Omega \mathcal M^k w^2\,dx .
\]
Here we used \(\nabla w=\nabla p^{k+1}\) on the set
\(\{p^{k+1}>p_H\}\) and \(\nabla w=0\) elsewhere. Since
\(n^k\ge0\) and \(\mathcal M^k\ge0\), the right-hand side is nonpositive.
The left-hand side is nonnegative by the previous inequality. Therefore
both sides must be zero.

It follows that \(w=0\), and hence \(p^{k+1}\le p_H\). Since
\(n^{k+1}\ge0\), we also have \(p^{k+1}\ge0\). Finally,
\(p^{k+1}=(n^{k+1})^\gamma\) gives
\[
    0\le n^{k+1}\le n_H .
\]
The proof is complete.
\end{proof}

\begin{proposition}[Energy stability]
\label{prop:time-discrete-energy}
Assume that \(n^k\ge0\). Let
\((n^{k+1},m^{k+1},q^{k+1})\) be a minimizer of
\eqref{eq:discrete-minimization}. Then
\begin{equation}\label{eq:time-discrete-energy}
\mathcal E(n^{k+1})
+
\frac{1}{2\tau}
\int_\Omega
\frac{|m^{k+1}|^2}{n^k}\,dx
+
\frac{1}{2\tau}
\int_\Omega
\frac{|q^{k+1}|^2}{\mathcal M^k}\,dx
\le
\mathcal E(n^k).
\end{equation}
In particular, \(\mathcal E(n^{k+1})\le \mathcal E(n^k)\).
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}
Since \(n^k\ge0\), we have \((n^k,0,0)\in\mathcal A^k\). By the
minimizing property,
\[
\mathcal J_\tau^k(n^{k+1},m^{k+1},q^{k+1})
\le
\mathcal J_\tau^k(n^k,0,0)
=
\mathcal E(n^k).
\]
Using the definition of \(\mathcal J_\tau^k\), we obtain
\eqref{eq:time-discrete-energy}. The last assertion follows since the
dissipation terms are nonnegative.
\end{proof}

\begin{remark}[Pure diffusion case]\label{rem:pure-diffusion}
If \(G\equiv0\), the reaction part is absent. We set \(r\equiv0\) in the
continuous Onsager formulation. At the time-discrete level, the variable
\(q\) and the reaction dissipation term in \eqref{eq:discrete-rayleighian}
are omitted. The admissible set becomes
\[
\mathcal A_0^k
=
\left\{
(n,m)\ \middle|\
n\ge0,\quad
n-n^k+\nabla\cdot m=0 \ \text{in } \Omega,\quad
m\cdot\nu=0 \ \text{on } \partial\Omega
\right\}.
\]
The minimization problem reduces to
\[
(n^{k+1},m^{k+1})
=
\operatorname*{arg\,min}_{(n,m)\in\mathcal A_0^k}
\left\{
\mathcal E(n)
+
\frac{1}{2\tau}
\int_\Omega \frac{|m|^2}{n^k}\,dx
\right\}.
\]
\end{remark}


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%


For clarity, we present the spatial discretization in one space dimension.
This setting contains the main ingredients needed for the structure-preserving
analysis, while the two-dimensional Cartesian extension used in the numerical
experiments is given in Appendix~\ref{app:2d-scheme}.

Let \(\Omega=(a,b)\), \(h=(b-a)/N\), and
\[
x_i=a+\left(i-\frac12\right)h,
\qquad 1\le i\le N .
\]
The value \(n_i^k\) approximates the density at the cell center \(x_i\)
and time \(t_k=k\tau\), and the pressure is given by
\[
p_i^k=(n_i^k)^\gamma .
\]
For a cell-centered grid function \(v=\{v_i\}_{i=1}^N\) and an interface
grid function \(F=\{F_{i+\frac12}\}_{i=0}^N\), we define
\[
(\delta_h v)_{i+\frac12}
=
\frac{v_{i+1}-v_i}{h},
\qquad 1\le i\le N-1,
\]
and
\[
(d_hF)_i
=
\frac{F_{i+\frac12}-F_{i-\frac12}}{h},
\qquad 1\le i\le N .
\]

Given \(n^k=\{n_i^k\}_{i=1}^N\), we determine
\(n^{k+1}=\{n_i^{k+1}\}_{i=1}^N\) with \(n_i^{k+1}\ge0\). Set
\(p_i^{k+1}=(n_i^{k+1})^\gamma\). For \(1\le i\le N-1\), let
\[
n_{i+\frac12}^k
=
\frac{n_i^k+n_{i+1}^k}{2}.
\]
We define
\begin{equation}
F_{i+\frac12}^{k+1}
=
n_{i+\frac12}^k
(\delta_h p^{k+1})_{i+\frac12},
\qquad 1\le i\le N-1 .
\label{eq:fd-flux}
\end{equation}
Then \(n^{k+1}\) satisfies
\begin{equation}
\frac{n_i^{k+1}-n_i^k}{\tau}
=
(d_hF^{k+1})_i
-
\mathcal M_i^k
\left(p_i^{k+1}-p_H\right),
\qquad 1\le i\le N .
\label{eq:fd-scheme}
\end{equation}
The no-flux boundary condition is imposed by
\begin{equation}
F_{\frac12}^{k+1}=F_{N+\frac12}^{k+1}=0 .
\label{eq:fd-no-flux}
\end{equation}
Here
\begin{equation}
\mathcal M_i^k
=
\begin{cases}
-\dfrac{n_i^kG(p_i^k)}{p_i^k-p_H}, & p_i^k\ne p_H,\\[1.2ex]
-n_i^kG'(p_H), & p_i^k=p_H .
\end{cases}
\label{eq:fd-reaction-mobility}
\end{equation}
Since \(p_i^{k+1}=(n_i^{k+1})^\gamma\), \eqref{eq:fd-scheme} is a
nonlinear system for \(n^{k+1}\).


\begin{proposition}[Existence, nonnegativity, and homeostatic upper bound]
\label{prop:fd-positivity-upper-bound}
Assume that \(n_i^k\ge 0\) for \(1\le i\le N\), and that \(G\) satisfies
\eqref{eq:g-assumption}--\eqref{eq:g-dissipative}. Then the fully discrete
scheme \eqref{eq:fd-flux}--\eqref{eq:fd-no-flux} admits a nonnegative
solution \(n^{k+1}\), namely
\[
n_i^{k+1}\ge 0,
\qquad 1\le i\le N .
\]
Moreover, if
\[
0\le n_i^k\le n_H:=p_H^{1/\gamma},
\qquad 1\le i\le N ,
\]
then the solution satisfies
\[
0\le n_i^{k+1}\le n_H,
\qquad
0\le p_i^{k+1}\le p_H,
\qquad 1\le i\le N .
\]
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}
We first show that \(M_i^k\ge 0\). If \(p_i^k\ne p_H\), then
\[
M_i^k
=
-\frac{n_i^kG(p_i^k)}{p_i^k-p_H}\ge 0
\]
by \(n_i^k\ge 0\) and \((p-p_H)G(p)\le 0\). If \(p_i^k=p_H\), then
\[
M_i^k=-n_i^kG'(p_H)\ge 0
\]
by \(G'(p)\le 0\).

We next prove the existence of a nonnegative solution. We write the
scheme in terms of the pressure variable \(p_i^{k+1}=(n_i^{k+1})^\gamma\).
For a trial pressure \(p=\{p_i\}_{i=1}^N\), define
\[
F_{i+\frac12}
=
n^k_{i+\frac12}(\delta_h p)_{i+\frac12},
\qquad 1\le i\le N-1,
\]
together with
\[
F_{\frac12}=F_{N+\frac12}=0 .
\]
Consider the functional
\[
\mathcal J_h(p)
=
h\sum_{i=1}^N
\left[
\frac{\gamma}{\gamma+1}p_i^{\frac{\gamma+1}{\gamma}}
-
n_i^k p_i
+
\frac{\tau}{2}M_i^k(p_i-p_H)^2
\right]
+
\frac{\tau h}{2}
\sum_{i=1}^{N-1}
n^k_{i+\frac12}
\left|(\delta_h p)_{i+\frac12}\right|^2
\]
on the closed convex set
\[
K_h=\{p\in\mathbb R^N:\ p_i\ge 0,\ 1\le i\le N\}.
\]
Since \(M_i^k\ge 0\) and \(n^k_{i+\frac12}\ge 0\), the functional
\(\mathcal J_h\) is convex on \(K_h\). Moreover, the term
\(p_i^{(\gamma+1)/\gamma}\) is superlinear on \([0,\infty)\), and hence
\(\mathcal J_h\) is coercive on \(K_h\). Therefore \(\mathcal J_h\) admits
a minimizer \(p^{k+1}\in K_h\).

It remains to show that this minimizer satisfies the finite difference
scheme. The first variation of \(\mathcal J_h\) has the form
\[
D\mathcal J_h(p)[\varphi]
=
h\sum_{i=1}^N R_i(p)\varphi_i ,
\]
where
\[
R_i(p)
=
p_i^{1/\gamma}
-
n_i^k
+
\tau M_i^k(p_i-p_H)
-
\tau (d_hF)_i .
\]
If \(p_i>0\), the Euler--Lagrange equation gives \(R_i(p)=0\). If
\(p_i=0\), the variational inequality on \(K_h\) gives \(R_i(p)\ge 0\).
On the other hand, since \(p_i=0\) is a minimum of the nonnegative grid
function \(p\), we have
\[
(d_hF)_i\ge 0 ,
\]
including the boundary cases because \(F_{\frac12}=F_{N+\frac12}=0\).
Thus
\[
R_i(p)
=
-n_i^k-\tau M_i^k p_H-\tau(d_hF)_i
\le 0 .
\]
Hence \(R_i(p)=0\) also when \(p_i=0\). Therefore the minimizer satisfies
\[
p_i^{1/\gamma}
-
n_i^k
+
\tau M_i^k(p_i-p_H)
-
\tau(d_hF)_i
=0,
\qquad 1\le i\le N .
\]
Setting
\[
n_i^{k+1}=(p_i^{k+1})^{1/\gamma}
\]
gives exactly \eqref{eq:fd-scheme}. Since \(p^{k+1}\in K_h\), we obtain
\(n_i^{k+1}\ge 0\).

We finally prove the upper bound. Assume that
\[
0\le n_i^k\le n_H,
\qquad 1\le i\le N .
\]
Suppose, by contradiction, that
\[
\max_{1\le i\le N} n_i^{k+1}>n_H .
\]
Let \(\ell\) be such that
\[
p_\ell^{k+1}
=
\max_{1\le i\le N} p_i^{k+1}.
\]
Then \(p_\ell^{k+1}>p_H\). Since \(p_\ell^{k+1}\) is a maximum and
\(n^k_{i+\frac12}\ge 0\), we have
\[
(d_hF^{k+1})_\ell\le 0 .
\]
Using the fully discrete scheme at \(i=\ell\), we obtain
\[
\frac{n_\ell^{k+1}-n_\ell^k}{\tau}
=
(d_hF^{k+1})_\ell
-
M_\ell^k(p_\ell^{k+1}-p_H)
\le 0 .
\]
Therefore
\[
n_\ell^{k+1}\le n_\ell^k\le n_H,
\]
which contradicts \(n_\ell^{k+1}>n_H\). Hence
\[
n_i^{k+1}\le n_H,
\qquad 1\le i\le N .
\]
Since \(p_i^{k+1}=(n_i^{k+1})^\gamma\), we also have
\[
p_i^{k+1}\le p_H,
\qquad 1\le i\le N .
\]
The proof is complete.
\end{proof}



We define the discrete modified energy by
\begin{equation}
\mathcal E_h(n)
=
h\sum_{i=1}^N
\left(
\frac{1}{\gamma+1}n_i^{\gamma+1}
-
p_Hn_i
\right).
\label{eq:fd-discrete-modified-energy}
\end{equation}

\begin{proposition}[Discrete energy dissipation]
\label{prop:fd-energy-dissipation}
Assume that \(n_i^k\ge0\) for \(1\le i\le N\), and that \(G\) satisfies
\eqref{eq:g-assumption} and \eqref{eq:g-dissipative}. Let
\(n^{k+1}\) be a nonnegative solution of
\eqref{eq:fd-flux}--\eqref{eq:fd-no-flux}. Then
\begin{align}
\mathcal E_h(n^{k+1})
&+
\tau h
\sum_{i=1}^{N-1}
n_{i+\frac12}^k
\left|
(\delta_hp^{k+1})_{i+\frac12}
\right|^2
+
\tau h
\sum_{i=1}^N
\mathcal M_i^k
\left|
p_i^{k+1}-p_H
\right|^2
\nonumber\\
&\le
\mathcal E_h(n^k).
\label{eq:fd-energy-dissipation}
\end{align}
In particular,
\[
\mathcal E_h(n^{k+1})\le \mathcal E_h(n^k).
\]
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}
First, by the assumptions on \(G\) and the definition of
\(\mathcal M_i^k\), we have \(\mathcal M_i^k\ge0\). Indeed, if
\(p_i^k\ne p_H\), this follows from \eqref{eq:g-dissipative}; if
\(p_i^k=p_H\), then
\[
\mathcal M_i^k=-n_i^kG'(p_H)\ge0 .
\]
Since \(n_i^k\ge0\), we also have \(n_{i+\frac12}^k\ge0\).

Let
\[
e(n)=\frac{1}{\gamma+1}n^{\gamma+1}-p_Hn .
\]
The function \(e\) is convex on \([0,\infty)\), and
\(e'(n)=n^\gamma-p_H\). Hence, for the nonnegative solution
\(n^{k+1}\),
\[
e(n_i^{k+1})-e(n_i^k)
\le
\left(p_i^{k+1}-p_H\right)
\left(n_i^{k+1}-n_i^k\right).
\]
Summing over \(i\) gives
\begin{equation}
\mathcal E_h(n^{k+1})-\mathcal E_h(n^k)
\le
h\sum_{i=1}^N
\left(p_i^{k+1}-p_H\right)
\left(n_i^{k+1}-n_i^k\right).
\label{eq:fd-convexity-step}
\end{equation}

Multiplying \eqref{eq:fd-scheme} by
\(\tau h(p_i^{k+1}-p_H)\) and summing over \(i\), we obtain
\begin{align}
h\sum_{i=1}^N
\left(p_i^{k+1}-p_H\right)
\left(n_i^{k+1}-n_i^k\right)
&=
\tau h
\sum_{i=1}^N
\left(p_i^{k+1}-p_H\right)(d_hF^{k+1})_i
\nonumber\\
&\quad
-
\tau h
\sum_{i=1}^N
\mathcal M_i^k
\left|p_i^{k+1}-p_H\right|^2 .
\label{eq:fd-testing-step}
\end{align}

Using the summation-by-parts identity
\[
h\sum_{i=1}^N v_i(d_hF)_i
=
-h\sum_{i=1}^{N-1}
F_{i+\frac12}(\delta_hv)_{i+\frac12},
\]
which holds under \(F_{\frac12}=F_{N+\frac12}=0\), we get
\[
h\sum_{i=1}^N
\left(p_i^{k+1}-p_H\right)(d_hF^{k+1})_i
=
-h\sum_{i=1}^{N-1}
F_{i+\frac12}^{k+1}
(\delta_hp^{k+1})_{i+\frac12}.
\]
By the definition of \(F_{i+\frac12}^{k+1}\), this becomes
\[
h\sum_{i=1}^N
\left(p_i^{k+1}-p_H\right)(d_hF^{k+1})_i
=
-h\sum_{i=1}^{N-1}
n_{i+\frac12}^k
\left|
(\delta_hp^{k+1})_{i+\frac12}
\right|^2 .
\]
Combining this identity with \eqref{eq:fd-convexity-step} and
\eqref{eq:fd-testing-step} yields
\begin{align*}
\mathcal E_h(n^{k+1})-\mathcal E_h(n^k)
&\le
-\tau h
\sum_{i=1}^{N-1}
n_{i+\frac12}^k
\left|
(\delta_hp^{k+1})_{i+\frac12}
\right|^2  \\
&\quad
-
\tau h
\sum_{i=1}^N
\mathcal M_i^k
\left|p_i^{k+1}-p_H\right|^2 .
\end{align*}
This is exactly \eqref{eq:fd-energy-dissipation}. Since both dissipation
terms are nonnegative, the monotonicity of \(\mathcal E_h\) follows.
\end{proof}


\subsection{Discrete limiting structure in the stiff-pressure regime}
\label{subsec:large-gamma-structure}

We now discuss the behavior of the fully discrete scheme in the
stiff-pressure regime $\gamma\to\infty$. The purpose of this subsection is
not to prove a full asymptotic-preserving result in the sense of deriving
the discrete pressure complementarity relation
\[
p\left(\Delta p+G(p)\right)=0
\]
at the fully discrete level. Such a result usually relies on a discrete
pressure equation and on estimates that are uniform with respect to
$\gamma$. Instead, for the present Onsager discretization, we prove a
fixed-grid limiting structure. More precisely, for fixed $h$ and $\tau$,
the scheme has a subsequential limit satisfying the congestion constraint,
the density-pressure complementarity relation, and a limiting finite
difference balance law.

We write explicitly the dependence on $\gamma$. The fully discrete scheme is
\begin{equation}
\frac{n_{\gamma,i}^{k+1}-n_{\gamma,i}^{k}}{\tau}
=
(d_hF_{\gamma}^{k+1})_i
-
M_{\gamma,i}^k
\left(p_{\gamma,i}^{k+1}-p_H\right),
\qquad
p_{\gamma,i}^{k+1}
=
\left(n_{\gamma,i}^{k+1}\right)^\gamma ,
\label{eq:gamma-fd-scheme}
\end{equation}
where
\begin{equation}
F_{\gamma,i+\frac12}^{k+1}
=
n_{\gamma,i+\frac12}^{k}
(\delta_h p_{\gamma}^{k+1})_{i+\frac12},
\qquad
n_{\gamma,i+\frac12}^{k}
=
\frac{n_{\gamma,i}^{k}+n_{\gamma,i+1}^{k}}{2},
\label{eq:gamma-fd-flux}
\end{equation}
with
\[
F_{\gamma,\frac12}^{k+1}
=
F_{\gamma,N+\frac12}^{k+1}
=
0.
\]
The reaction mobility is
\begin{equation}
M_{\gamma,i}^k
=
\begin{cases}
\displaystyle
-
\frac{n_{\gamma,i}^kG(p_{\gamma,i}^k)}
{p_{\gamma,i}^k-p_H},
&
p_{\gamma,i}^k\ne p_H,
\\[2mm]
\displaystyle
-n_{\gamma,i}^kG'(p_H),
&
p_{\gamma,i}^k=p_H.
\end{cases}
\label{eq:gamma-mobility}
\end{equation}

\begin{proposition}[Fixed-grid stiff-pressure limit]
\label{prop:fixed-grid-gamma-limit}
Assume that $G\in C^1([0,\infty))$, $G(p_H)=0$, and $G'(p)\le0$ for
$p\ge0$. Assume that the initial data satisfy
\[
0\le p_{\gamma,i}^0\le p_H,
\qquad
p_{\gamma,i}^0=(n_{\gamma,i}^0)^\gamma,
\qquad
1\le i\le N .
\]
Let $h>0$ and $\tau>0$ be fixed. Suppose that, for a fixed time level $k$,
\[
n_{\gamma,i}^{k}\to n_i^k,
\qquad
p_{\gamma,i}^{k}\to p_i^k,
\qquad
1\le i\le N,
\]
along a subsequence as $\gamma\to\infty$. Then there exists a further
subsequence such that
\[
n_{\gamma,i}^{k+1}\to n_i^{k+1},
\qquad
p_{\gamma,i}^{k+1}\to p_i^{k+1},
\qquad
1\le i\le N .
\]
The limiting variables satisfy
\begin{equation}
0\le n_i^{k+1}\le 1,
\qquad
0\le p_i^{k+1}\le p_H,
\qquad
p_i^{k+1}(1-n_i^{k+1})=0 .
\label{eq:limit-density-pressure-complementarity}
\end{equation}
Moreover, they solve the limiting finite difference system
\begin{equation}
\frac{n_i^{k+1}-n_i^{k}}{\tau}
=
(d_hF^{k+1})_i
-
M_i^k
\left(p_i^{k+1}-p_H\right),
\qquad
1\le i\le N,
\label{eq:limit-fd-balance}
\end{equation}
where
\begin{equation}
F_{i+\frac12}^{k+1}
=
n_{i+\frac12}^{k}
(\delta_h p^{k+1})_{i+\frac12},
\qquad
n_{i+\frac12}^{k}
=
\frac{n_i^k+n_{i+1}^k}{2},
\label{eq:limit-fd-flux}
\end{equation}
with
\[
F_{\frac12}^{k+1}
=
F_{N+\frac12}^{k+1}
=
0,
\]
and
\begin{equation}
M_i^k
=
\begin{cases}
\displaystyle
-
\frac{n_i^kG(p_i^k)}
{p_i^k-p_H},
&
p_i^k\ne p_H,
\\[2mm]
\displaystyle
-n_i^kG'(p_H),
&
p_i^k=p_H.
\end{cases}
\label{eq:limit-mobility}
\end{equation}
Equivalently, the limiting variables satisfy the discrete complementarity
form
\begin{equation}
p_i^{k+1}
\left[
\frac{1-n_i^{k}}{\tau}
-
(d_hF^{k+1})_i
+
M_i^k
\left(p_i^{k+1}-p_H\right)
\right]
=0,
\qquad
1\le i\le N .
\label{eq:limit-pressure-complementarity-form}
\end{equation}
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}
By the bound-preserving property of the fully discrete scheme, we have
\[
0\le n_{\gamma,i}^{k+1}\le p_H^{1/\gamma},
\qquad
0\le p_{\gamma,i}^{k+1}\le p_H,
\qquad
1\le i\le N .
\]
Since the grid is fixed and contains only finitely many points, there
exists a subsequence such that
\[
n_{\gamma,i}^{k+1}\to n_i^{k+1},
\qquad
p_{\gamma,i}^{k+1}\to p_i^{k+1},
\qquad
1\le i\le N .
\]
Passing to the limit in the above bounds gives
\[
0\le n_i^{k+1}\le 1,
\qquad
0\le p_i^{k+1}\le p_H .
\]

We next prove the complementarity relation. Since
\[
p_{\gamma,i}^{k+1}
=
\left(n_{\gamma,i}^{k+1}\right)^\gamma ,
\]
we have
\[
n_{\gamma,i}^{k+1}
=
\left(p_{\gamma,i}^{k+1}\right)^{1/\gamma}.
\]
If $p_i^{k+1}>0$, then $p_{\gamma,i}^{k+1}$ is bounded away from zero for
all sufficiently large $\gamma$. Hence
\[
n_{\gamma,i}^{k+1}
=
\left(p_{\gamma,i}^{k+1}\right)^{1/\gamma}
\longrightarrow 1 .
\]
Therefore $p_i^{k+1}>0$ implies $n_i^{k+1}=1$, which is equivalent to
\[
p_i^{k+1}(1-n_i^{k+1})=0 .
\]
This proves \eqref{eq:limit-density-pressure-complementarity}.

It remains to pass to the limit in the finite difference equation. Since
$h$ is fixed, all difference operators are finite-dimensional linear
operators. From the convergence of $n_\gamma^k$ and $p_\gamma^{k+1}$, we get
\[
F_{\gamma,i+\frac12}^{k+1}
=
n_{\gamma,i+\frac12}^{k}
(\delta_h p_{\gamma}^{k+1})_{i+\frac12}
\longrightarrow
n_{i+\frac12}^{k}
(\delta_h p^{k+1})_{i+\frac12}
=
F_{i+\frac12}^{k+1}.
\]
Thus
\[
(d_hF_{\gamma}^{k+1})_i
\longrightarrow
(d_hF^{k+1})_i .
\]

We now consider the reaction mobility. If $p_i^k\ne p_H$, then
\[
M_{\gamma,i}^k
=
-
\frac{n_{\gamma,i}^kG(p_{\gamma,i}^k)}
{p_{\gamma,i}^k-p_H}
\longrightarrow
-
\frac{n_i^kG(p_i^k)}
{p_i^k-p_H}.
\]
If $p_i^k=p_H$, then $G(p_H)=0$ and $G\in C^1([0,\infty))$ imply
\[
\frac{G(p_{\gamma,i}^k)}{p_{\gamma,i}^k-p_H}
\longrightarrow
G'(p_H),
\]
and hence
\[
M_{\gamma,i}^k
\longrightarrow
-n_i^kG'(p_H).
\]
Therefore, in all cases,
\[
M_{\gamma,i}^k
\longrightarrow
M_i^k .
\]
Combining this convergence with
$p_{\gamma,i}^{k+1}\to p_i^{k+1}$ gives
\[
M_{\gamma,i}^k
\left(p_{\gamma,i}^{k+1}-p_H\right)
\longrightarrow
M_i^k
\left(p_i^{k+1}-p_H\right).
\]
Passing to the limit in \eqref{eq:gamma-fd-scheme} gives
\eqref{eq:limit-fd-balance}.

Finally, multiplying \eqref{eq:limit-fd-balance} by $p_i^{k+1}$ and using
the complementarity relation
$p_i^{k+1}(1-n_i^{k+1})=0$, we obtain
\eqref{eq:limit-pressure-complementarity-form}. The proof is complete.
\end{proof}

\begin{remark}
The limiting relation \eqref{eq:limit-pressure-complementarity-form} is the
discrete stiff-pressure structure naturally associated with the present
Onsager scheme. It should not be confused with the stronger discrete
pressure complementarity relation
\[
p_i(\delta_h^2p_i+G(p_i))=0,
\]
which can be derived for certain fully implicit upwind schemes by passing
to the limit in a discrete pressure equation.

Nevertheless, \eqref{eq:limit-pressure-complementarity-form} is consistent
with the Hele--Shaw pressure equation. Indeed, in a saturated region where
$n_i^k\approx 1$ and $p_i^{k+1}\approx p_i^k$, one has
\[
-
M_i^k(p_i^{k+1}-p_H)
\approx
G(p_i^{k+1}).
\]
In addition, if the neighboring cells are also saturated, then
\[
(d_hF^{k+1})_i
\approx
(\delta_h^2p^{k+1})_i .
\]
Thus the limiting balance formally reduces to
\[
(\delta_h^2p^{k+1})_i+G(p_i^{k+1})\approx 0,
\]
which is the finite difference form of the Hele--Shaw pressure equation in
the saturated region.
\end{remark}


