\subsection{Accuracy and structure-preserving properties for the porous medium equation}
\label{subsec:numerical-barenblatt}

We first examine the proposed scheme for the pure porous medium equation.
The growth term is removed by taking
\[
G(p)=0 .
\]
Since \(p=n^\gamma\), the model reduces to
\begin{equation}
\partial_t n
=
\partial_x\left(n\partial_x n^\gamma\right)
=
\frac{\gamma}{\gamma+1}\partial_{xx} n^{\gamma+1}.
\label{eq:pme-test-equation}
\end{equation}
This equation admits a time-shifted Barenblatt solution. Let
\[
\kappa=\frac{\gamma}{\gamma+1},
\qquad
\beta=\frac{1}{\gamma+2},
\qquad
s=\kappa(t+t_0).
\]
The exact solution is given by
\begin{equation}
n_{\rm ex}(x,t)
=
s^{-\beta}
\left(
C_{\rm bar}
-
\frac{\beta\gamma}{2(\gamma+1)}
\frac{x^2}{s^{2\beta}}
\right)_+^{1/\gamma},
\label{eq:barenblatt-profile}
\end{equation}
where \((z)_+=\max\{z,0\}\). The initial condition is chosen as
\[
n_0(x)=n_{\rm ex}(x,0).
\]

The computation is performed on the interval \([-5,5]\) with no-flux
boundary conditions at both endpoints. For the profile comparison, we use
\[
h=\frac{1}{64},
\qquad
\tau=0.01h,
\qquad
T=0.1,
\qquad
t_0=0.01 .
\]
Two values of the nonlinear exponent are considered. For \(\gamma=3\), we
take \(C_{\rm bar}=1\). For \(\gamma=20\), we take
\(C_{\rm bar}=0.1\), so that the support of the exact solution remains
well inside the computational domain.

Figure~\ref{fig:example1-profiles} compares the numerical solution with
the Barenblatt profile at \(T=0.1\). The numerical solution agrees well
with the exact solution for both values of \(\gamma\). As \(\gamma\)
increases, the profile becomes flatter in the interior and sharper near
the free boundary. This shows that the scheme captures the degenerate
diffusion mechanism accurately.

\begin{figure}[htp!]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.9\textwidth]{example1_figure1.eps}
  \caption{Comparison between the numerical solution and the Barenblatt
  profile for the porous medium equation with \(G(p)=0\). The left panel
  corresponds to \(\gamma=3\) with \(C_{\rm bar}=1\), and the right panel
  corresponds to \(\gamma=20\) with \(C_{\rm bar}=0.1\). The parameters are
  \(h=1/64\), \(\tau=0.01h\), and \(T=0.1\).}
  \label{fig:example1-profiles}
\end{figure}

We next quantify the spatial convergence behavior. The discrete \(L^1\)
error at time \(t_k\) is defined by
\[
\operatorname{err}_1(t_k)
=
h\sum_{i=1}^N
\left|n_i^k-n_{\rm ex}(x_i,t_k)\right|.
\]
For each mesh size, we compute
\[
e_h
=
\max_{t_k\in[0.05,T]}
\operatorname{err}_1(t_k).
\]
The observed order between two consecutive meshes is computed by
\[
\mathrm{order}
=
\log_2\frac{e_h}{e_{h/2}} .
\]
The results are reported in Table~\ref{tab:example1-spatial-convergence}.
For both values of \(\gamma\), the error decreases under mesh refinement.
The observed rates are close to first order for \(\gamma=20\), while a
slightly higher rate is obtained for \(\gamma=3\). This behavior is
consistent with the limited regularity of the Barenblatt profile near the
moving interface.

\begin{table}[htp!]
\centering
\caption{Discrete \(L^1\) errors and observed spatial convergence orders
for the Barenblatt test with \(G(p)=0\). The error is measured by
\(e_h=\max_{t_k\in[0.05,T]}\operatorname{err}_1(t_k)\).}
\label{tab:example1-spatial-convergence}
\renewcommand{\arraystretch}{1.15}
\begin{tabular}{cccccc}
\hline
\(\gamma\) & quantity & \(1/32\) & \(1/64\) & \(1/128\) & \(1/256\) \\
\hline
\multirow{2}{*}{3}
& \(e_h\) & \(1.81{\times}10^{-2}\) & \(8.22{\times}10^{-3}\)
          & \(3.48{\times}10^{-3}\) & \(1.15{\times}10^{-3}\) \\
& order   & -- & 1.14 & 1.24 & 1.61 \\
\hline
\multirow{2}{*}{20}
& \(e_h\) & \(4.06{\times}10^{-2}\) & \(1.91{\times}10^{-2}\)
          & \(9.14{\times}10^{-3}\) & \(4.50{\times}10^{-3}\) \\
& order   & -- & 1.09 & 1.06 & 1.02 \\
\hline
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

We also examine the temporal accuracy of the fully implicit time
discretization. To reduce the influence of the spatial error, the mesh size
is fixed sufficiently small and the time step is successively refined. The
temporal error is measured by
\[
e_\tau
=
\max_{t_k\in[0.05,T]}
h\sum_{i=1}^N
\left|n_i^k-n_{\rm ex}(x_i,t_k)\right|.
\]
The observed temporal order is computed by
\[
\mathrm{order}
=
\log_2\frac{e_\tau}{e_{\tau/2}} .
\]
The results in Table~\ref{tab:example1-temporal-convergence} show the
expected first-order temporal accuracy of the fully implicit scheme.

\begin{table}[htp!]
\centering
\caption{Temporal errors and observed orders for the Barenblatt test with
\(G(p)=0\). A sufficiently fine spatial mesh is used so that the temporal
error dominates.}
\label{tab:example1-temporal-convergence}
\renewcommand{\arraystretch}{1.15}
\begin{tabular}{cccccc}
\hline
\(\gamma\) & quantity & \(\tau_0\) & \(\tau_0/2\) & \(\tau_0/4\) & \(\tau_0/8\) \\
\hline
\multirow{2}{*}{3}
& \(e_\tau\) &  &  &  &  \\
& order & -- &  &  &  \\
\hline
\multirow{2}{*}{20}
& \(e_\tau\) &  &  &  &  \\
& order & -- &  &  &  \\
\hline
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

We finally examine mass conservation and energy dissipation. Since
\(G(p)=0\), the continuous equation conserves the total mass. The discrete
mass is defined by
\[
M_h(t_k)=h\sum_{i=1}^N n_i^k ,
\]
and the relative mass variation is computed by
\[
\frac{M_h(t_k)-M_h(0)}{M_h(0)} .
\]
For this test, the discrete energy is
\begin{equation}
\mathcal E_h(n^k)
=
h\sum_{i=1}^N
\frac{1}{\gamma+1}(n_i^k)^{\gamma+1}.
\label{eq:example1-energy}
\end{equation}
The structure-preserving test is performed with the same mesh size
\(h=1/64\) and time step \(\tau=0.01h\). The computation is continued to
\(T_{\rm sp}=1\) in order to better display the long-time behavior.

Figure~\ref{fig:example1-mass-energy} shows the relative mass variation
and the normalized energy \(\mathcal E_h(n^k)/\mathcal E_h(n^0)\). The mass
variation remains at the level of round-off errors, and the discrete
energy decreases monotonically along the numerical solution. This confirms
the conservative and dissipative properties of the scheme in the pure
diffusion case.

\begin{figure}[htp!]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.9\textwidth]{example1_figure3.eps}
  \caption{Mass conservation and energy dissipation for the Barenblatt
  test with \(G(p)=0\). The left panel shows the relative mass variation
  for \(\gamma=3\) and \(\gamma=20\). The right panel shows the normalized
  discrete energy \(\mathcal E_h(n^k)/\mathcal E_h(n^0)\) for
  \(\gamma=3\) and \(\gamma=20\).}
  \label{fig:example1-mass-energy}
\end{figure}

We close this test by examining the temporal resolution required for
compactly supported solutions. Although the proposed scheme is
unconditionally energy stable, the accurate resolution of the moving free
boundary requires a sufficiently fine time step. This should be understood
as an accuracy requirement rather than a stability restriction.

To illustrate this point, we compare spatial refinements with fixed time
steps and with coupled choices of the form \(\tau=Ch\). For \(\gamma=3\),
we take \(C_{\rm bar}=1\) and use \(\tau=0.05h\). For \(\gamma=20\), we
take \(C_{\rm bar}=0.1\) and use \(\tau=0.01h\). The results are shown in
Figure~\ref{fig:example1-mesh-time-coupling}.

\begin{figure}[htp!]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.9\textwidth]{example1_figure4.eps}
  \caption{Mesh-time coupling test for compactly supported Barenblatt
  solutions. The left panel corresponds to \(\gamma=3\) with
  \(C_{\rm bar}=1\), and the right panel corresponds to \(\gamma=20\) with
  \(C_{\rm bar}=0.1\). For fixed time steps, spatial refinement alone does
  not always lead to a consistent decrease of the error. In contrast, the
  coupled choices \(\tau=0.05h\) for \(\gamma=3\) and \(\tau=0.01h\) for
  \(\gamma=20\) give a more regular error decay. This illustrates a
  time-resolution requirement for accuracy near the moving free boundary,
  not a stability restriction.}
  \label{fig:example1-mesh-time-coupling}
\end{figure}


\subsection{Structure-preserving test with nonzero growth}
\label{subsec:numerical-growth}

We next consider a test with a nonzero growth term. The purpose of this
test is to examine the bound-preserving property and the modified energy
dissipation of the fully discrete scheme. We take
\[
G(p)=p_H-p,
\qquad
p_H=1 .
\]
Then
\[
(p-p_H)G(p)=-(p-p_H)^2\le0,
\]
which is consistent with the dissipation condition used in the theoretical
analysis. The corresponding homeostatic density is
\[
n_H=p_H^{1/\gamma}=1 .
\]

The computational domain is \([-5,5]\), and the initial density is chosen
as
\[
n_0(x)=0.8\,\mathbf 1_{[-1,1]}(x).
\]
Thus the initial data are compactly supported and satisfy
\[
0\le n_0(x)\le n_H .
\]
In this test, we use
\[
\gamma=10,
\qquad
h=0.025,
\qquad
\tau=10^{-4},
\qquad
T=2 .
\]
The nonlinear algebraic system at each time step is solved by the damped
Newton iteration described above.

Figure~\ref{fig:example2-profiles} shows the evolution of the density and
pressure at several times. The density remains nonnegative and expands
with finite speed. Inside the support, the density increases toward the
homeostatic value \(n_H=1\) without exceeding it. The pressure develops a
cap-shaped profile in the region occupied by the population and remains
close to zero near the free boundary. This behavior is consistent with
the pressure-inhibited growth mechanism.

\begin{figure}[htp!]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.9\textwidth]{example2_figure1.eps}
  \caption{Density and pressure profiles for the model with
  \(G(p)=p_H-p\) and \(p_H=1\). The left panel shows the density profiles
  and the right panel shows the pressure profiles at \(t=0,0.5,1,2\).
  The parameters are \(\gamma=10\), \(h=0.025\), \(\tau=10^{-4}\), and
  \(T=2\).}
  \label{fig:example2-profiles}
\end{figure}

We then examine the numerical bounds and the modified energy. For the
choice \(G(p)=p_H-p\), the continuous model is associated with the
modified energy
\[
\int_\Omega
\left(
\frac{1}{\gamma+1}n^{\gamma+1}
-
p_H n
\right)\,dx .
\]
Accordingly, we compute the discrete modified energy by
\begin{equation}
\mathcal E_h(n^k)
=
h\sum_{i=1}^N
\left(
\frac{1}{\gamma+1}(n_i^k)^{\gamma+1}
-
p_H n_i^k
\right).
\label{eq:example2-modified-energy}
\end{equation}

Figure~\ref{fig:example2-bounds-energy} displays the minimum and maximum
values of the density, the maximum value of the pressure, and the
modified energy. The numerical solution satisfies
\[
\min_i n_i^k\ge0,
\qquad
\max_i n_i^k\le n_H,
\qquad
\max_i p_i^k\le p_H
\]
throughout the computation, up to round-off errors. The modified energy
is nonincreasing in time. These results confirm that the scheme preserves
the expected bounds and the modified energy dissipation in the presence
of a nonzero growth term.

\begin{figure}[htp!]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.9\textwidth]{example2_figure2.eps}
  \caption{Bounds and modified energy dissipation for the model with
  \(G(p)=p_H-p\) and \(p_H=1\). The left panel shows \(\min_i n_i^k\),
  \(\max_i n_i^k\), and \(\max_i p_i^k\), together with the reference
  level \(n_H=p_H=1\). The right panel shows the modified energy
  \(\mathcal E_h(n^k)\).}
  \label{fig:example2-bounds-energy}
\end{figure}



\subsection{Large-\texorpdfstring{\(\gamma\)}{gamma} behavior and the Hele--Shaw limit}
\label{subsec:numerical-large-gamma}

We next examine the behavior of the proposed scheme in the nearly
incompressible regime. We take
\[
G(p)=1-p,
\qquad
p_H=1 .
\]
In the formal limit \(\gamma\to\infty\), the density converges to a
patch-type solution and the pressure satisfies a Hele--Shaw free boundary
problem. For a symmetric saturated interval \((-R(t),R(t))\), the limiting
pressure satisfies
\[
-p_{\infty,xx}=1-p_\infty,
\qquad |x|<R(t),
\]
together with the boundary condition
\[
p_\infty(\pm R(t),t)=0 .
\]
Hence
\begin{equation}
p_\infty(x,t)
=
\left(
1-\frac{\cosh x}{\cosh R(t)}
\right)_+,
\qquad
n_\infty(x,t)=\mathbf 1_{[-R(t),R(t)]}(x).
\label{eq:example3-hs-solution}
\end{equation}
The normal velocity law gives
\[
R'(t)=-\partial_x p_\infty(R(t),t)=\tanh R(t),
\qquad
R(0)=R_0 .
\]
Therefore
\begin{equation}
R(t)=\operatorname{arsinh}\left(e^t\sinh R_0\right).
\label{eq:example3-hs-radius}
\end{equation}

To reduce the initial layer, we use well-prepared initial data. Given
\(R_0=1\), we define
\[
p_0(x)
=
\left(
1-\frac{\cosh x}{\cosh R_0}
\right)_+
\]
and set
\begin{equation}
n_0^\gamma(x)=p_0(x)^{1/\gamma}.
\label{eq:example3-well-prepared}
\end{equation}
Then
\[
(n_0^\gamma(x))^\gamma=p_0(x),
\]
so that the initial pressure agrees with the limiting Hele--Shaw pressure
at \(t=0\).

The computations are performed on the interval \([-5,5]\). We fix
\[
N=6400,
\qquad
h=\frac{10}{N},
\qquad
\tau=10^{-4},
\qquad
T=1 .
\]
For the profile comparison, we display the numerical solutions for
\[
\gamma=3,\quad 20,\quad 200 .
\]

Figure~\ref{fig:example3-profiles} shows the numerical density and
pressure at \(T=1\), together with the explicit limiting profiles in
\eqref{eq:example3-hs-solution}. As \(\gamma\) increases, the density
approaches the characteristic function \(n_\infty\), while the pressure
approaches the limiting Hele--Shaw pressure. The density develops a
sharper transition layer near the moving boundary. In contrast, the
pressure remains continuous and is less affected by the interfacial
transition.

\begin{figure}[htp!]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.9\textwidth]{example3_figure1.eps}
  \caption{Large-\(\gamma\) behavior in one dimension. The left panel shows density profiles at \(T=1\). The right panel shows pressure profiles at \(T=1\). The black dotted curves denote the explicit Hele--Shaw limit.}
  \label{fig:example3-profiles}
\end{figure}

We also give a quantitative comparison with the explicit Hele--Shaw
limit. The discrete \(L^1\) errors at \(T=1\) are defined by
\begin{align}
{\rm err}_{n}^{\gamma}(T)
&=
h\sum_{i=1}^N
\left|
n_i^\gamma(T)-n_\infty(x_i,T)
\right|,
\label{eq:example3-error-n}
\\
{\rm err}_{p}^{\gamma}(T)
&=
h\sum_{i=1}^N
\left|
p_i^\gamma(T)-p_\infty(x_i,T)
\right|.
\label{eq:example3-error-p}
\end{align}
The results are reported in Figure~\ref{fig:example3-errors} for
representative values of \(\gamma\) in the large-\(\gamma\) regime. Both
errors decrease as \(\gamma\) increases, which indicates that the
numerical solution approaches the Hele--Shaw limit. The pressure error is
smaller and decreases more regularly, since the limiting pressure is
continuous. The density error is larger because the limiting density is a
characteristic function and the numerical density contains a thin
transition layer near the free boundary.

This experiment is intended to demonstrate the asymptotic trend toward
the Hele--Shaw limit. We do not use it to claim a rigorous convergence
rate with respect to \(\gamma\), since the reported errors also contain
spatial and temporal discretization errors.

\begin{figure}[htp!]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.65\textwidth]{example3_figure3.eps}
  \caption{Final-time discrete \(L^1\) errors of the density and pressure with respect to the explicit Hele--Shaw limit with fixed \(N=6400\).}
  \label{fig:example3-errors}
\end{figure}


\subsection{Two-dimensional free boundary evolutions}
\label{subsec:numerical-2d}

We finally present two-dimensional simulations to illustrate the robustness
of the proposed scheme for free boundary evolutions with topology changes.
In this part, we consider
\[
G(p)=1-p,
\qquad
p_H=1,
\qquad
p=n^\gamma .
\]
The density and pressure are computed on a uniform Cartesian grid, and
the homogeneous no-flux boundary condition is imposed on the boundary of
the computational domain. In the plots below, the level set \(n=0.5\) is
used to visualize the numerical free boundary.

\subsubsection{Hole filling from an annular initial density}
\label{subsubsec:numerical-annulus}

We first consider an annular initial density. The computational domain is
\[
\Omega=[-5,5]^2 .
\]
The initial condition is chosen as
\[
n_0(x,y)
=
0.8\,\mathbf 1_{\{r_{\rm in}\le \sqrt{x^2+y^2}\le r_{\rm out}\}},
\qquad
r_{\rm in}=0.8,
\qquad
r_{\rm out}=2.0 .
\]
In this example, we use
\[
\gamma=40,
\qquad
\tau=10^{-3},
\qquad
T=2 .
\]
This example is designed to test whether the numerical method can capture
the simultaneous expansion of the outer boundary and contraction of the
inner boundary.

Figure~\ref{fig:annulus-topview} shows top views of the density at
selected times. The black curves denote the level set \(n=0.5\). The
annular region expands outward, while the hole shrinks and eventually
disappears. The computation therefore captures the transition from a
doubly connected region to a simply connected tumor region.

\begin{figure}[htp!]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.95\textwidth]{example5_figure1.eps}
  \caption{Top views of the annular density evolution. The panels show
  \(n(x,y,t)\) at selected times. The black curves denote the level set
  \(n=0.5\), which is used to visualize the moving free boundary.}
  \label{fig:annulus-topview}
\end{figure}

The corresponding centerline sections are shown in
Figure~\ref{fig:annulus-sections}. The density profiles along \(y=0\)
give a more detailed view of the motion of the inner and outer interfaces.
The inner interface moves toward the origin and disappears, while the
outer interface keeps moving outward. This confirms the hole-filling
behavior observed in the top-view plots.

\begin{figure}[htp!]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.95\textwidth]{example5_figure2.eps}
  \caption{Density sections for the annular initial density along the line
  \(y=0\). The six panels correspond to the same time levels as in
  Figure~\ref{fig:annulus-topview}. The vertical dashed lines mark the
  crossings of the level \(n=0.5\).}
  \label{fig:annulus-sections}
\end{figure}

\subsubsection{Merging of two tumor patches}
\label{subsubsec:numerical-twodisks}

We next consider the merging of two initially separated tumor patches. The
computational domain is
\[
\Omega=[-5,5]^2 .
\]
The initial density is
\[
n_0(x,y)
=
0.8\,\mathbf 1_{B((-c_0,0),r_0)\cup B((c_0,0),r_0)},
\qquad
r_0=0.8,
\qquad
c_0=1.4 .
\]
Here \(B(z,r)\) denotes the disk centered at \(z\) with radius \(r\). This
example is used to examine whether the method can handle the merging of
two connected components.

Figure~\ref{fig:twodisks-topview} shows top views of the density at
selected times. The two components initially expand separately. They then
touch each other and merge into a single connected region. The black level
curves show that the numerical free boundary remains well resolved during
the merging process.

\begin{figure}[htp!]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.95\textwidth]{example6_figure1.eps}
  \caption{Top views of the merging of two tumor patches. The panels show
  \(n(x,y,t)\) at selected times. The black curves denote the level set
  \(n=0.5\), which is used to visualize the moving free boundary.}
  \label{fig:twodisks-topview}
\end{figure}

The centerline sections along \(y=0\) are shown in
Figure~\ref{fig:twodisks-sections}. At early times, the density profiles
contain two separated components. As time evolves, the two interfaces move
toward each other, the gap between the two patches closes, and a single
connected density profile is formed. This provides a one-dimensional view
of the topology change shown in Figure~\ref{fig:twodisks-topview}.

\begin{figure}[htp!]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.95\textwidth]{example6_figure2.eps}
  \caption{Density sections for the merging of two tumor patches along the
  line \(y=0\). The six panels correspond to the same time levels as in
  Figure~\ref{fig:twodisks-topview}. The vertical dashed lines mark the
  crossings of the level \(n=0.5\).}
  \label{fig:twodisks-sections}
\end{figure}

These two examples show that the proposed scheme can robustly capture
large deformations and topology changes of the numerical free boundary.
In particular, it resolves both the disappearance of an inner hole and
the merging of two initially disconnected tumor patches.


\section{Conclusion}

We have developed a structure-preserving finite difference method for a
pressure-driven tumor growth model with pressure-dependent proliferation.
The scheme is constructed from the Onsager variational principle by using a
modified energy shifted by the homeostatic pressure. This modification makes
the reaction contribution dissipative under the pressure-inhibition
assumption and allows the transport and growth mechanisms to be incorporated
into a unified Rayleighian formulation.

The resulting time-discrete scheme is obtained from a constrained
minimization problem, while the fully discrete scheme uses explicit
mobilities and an implicit pressure update. We proved that the method
preserves the nonnegativity of the density, the homeostatic upper bound, and
a discrete modified energy dissipation law. These properties are consistent
with the structural behavior of the continuous model.

The numerical results confirm the theoretical findings. The method
accurately captures Barenblatt profiles in the pure diffusion case,
preserves mass and energy dissipation, and remains stable in the presence of
nonzero growth. In the large-\(\gamma\) regime, the numerical density and
pressure approach the corresponding Hele--Shaw limit. Two-dimensional
simulations also show that the method can robustly handle free boundary
motion with topology changes, including hole filling and the merging of
separated tumor patches.

Future work will focus on extensions to more complex tumor growth models,
including nutrient effects, chemotaxis, and multiple cell populations, as
well as adaptive implementations for sharper resolution of free boundaries.



\appendix

\section{Implementation of the nonlinear solver}
\label{app:nonlinear-solver}

This appendix describes the nonlinear solver used for the fully discrete
scheme. At each time step, the coefficients \(n^k_{i+\frac12}\) and
\(M_i^k\) are evaluated explicitly from the known solution at time
\(t_k\). Consequently, the nonlinear unknown can be chosen as the
pressure \(p^{k+1}=\{p_i^{k+1}\}_{i=1}^N\). The density is then recovered
by
\[
n_i^{k+1}=(p_i^{k+1})^{1/\gamma}.
\]

For a trial pressure \(p=\{p_i\}_{i=1}^N\), define the numerical flux by
\[
F_{i+\frac12}(p)
=
n^k_{i+\frac12}\frac{p_{i+1}-p_i}{h},
\qquad 1\le i\le N-1,
\]
together with the no-flux boundary condition
\[
F_{\frac12}(p)=F_{N+\frac12}(p)=0.
\]
The nonlinear system is written in the residual form
\begin{equation}
\mathcal R_i(p)
=
p_i^{1/\gamma}
-
n_i^k
+
\tau M_i^k(p_i-p_H)
-
\tau (d_hF(p))_i
=0,
\qquad 1\le i\le N .
\label{eq:app-newton-residual}
\end{equation}
Solving \eqref{eq:app-newton-residual} gives \(p^{k+1}\), and the fully
discrete update is completed by setting
\[
n_i^{k+1}=(p_i^{k+1})^{1/\gamma}.
\]

We solve \eqref{eq:app-newton-residual} by a damped Newton iteration.
Given an approximation \(p^{[\ell]}\), the Newton correction
\(s^{[\ell]}\) is determined from
\[
\mathcal J(p^{[\ell]})s^{[\ell]}
=
-\mathcal R(p^{[\ell]}),
\]
where \(\mathcal J(p)\) denotes the Jacobian matrix of
\(\mathcal R(p)\). In one space dimension, the nonzero entries of
\(\mathcal J(p)\) are given by
\begin{align}
\mathcal J_{i,i}(p)
&=
\frac1\gamma p_i^{1/\gamma-1}
+
\tau M_i^k
+
\frac{\tau}{h^2}
\left(
n^k_{i+\frac12}
+
n^k_{i-\frac12}
\right),
\label{eq:app-newton-jac-diag}
\\
\mathcal J_{i,i+1}(p)
&=
-\frac{\tau}{h^2}n^k_{i+\frac12},
\qquad
1\le i\le N-1,
\label{eq:app-newton-jac-upper}
\\
\mathcal J_{i,i-1}(p)
&=
-\frac{\tau}{h^2}n^k_{i-\frac12},
\qquad
2\le i\le N.
\label{eq:app-newton-jac-lower}
\end{align}
Here the convention
\[
n^k_{\frac12}=n^k_{N+\frac12}=0
\]
is used, which is consistent with the no-flux boundary condition. Hence,
in one space dimension, \(\mathcal J(p)\) is a tridiagonal matrix.

To preserve nonnegativity during the nonlinear iteration, the Newton
step is combined with a backtracking line search. Starting from
\(\alpha_\ell=1\), the damping parameter is successively reduced by
\[
\alpha_\ell \leftarrow \frac{\alpha_\ell}{2}
\]
until the candidate update
\[
p^{[\ell]}+\alpha_\ell s^{[\ell]}
\]
satisfies
\[
p_i^{[\ell]}+\alpha_\ell s_i^{[\ell]}\ge 0,
\qquad 1\le i\le N,
\]
and the residual decrease condition
\[
\|\mathcal R(p^{[\ell]}+\alpha_\ell s^{[\ell]})\|_2
\le
(1-c\alpha_\ell)\|\mathcal R(p^{[\ell]})\|_2 .
\]
In all computations, we take \(c=10^{-4}\). The new iterate is then
defined by
\[
p^{[\ell+1]}=p^{[\ell]}+\alpha_\ell s^{[\ell]}.
\]

The Newton iteration is terminated when
\[
\frac{\|\mathcal R(p^{[\ell]})\|_\infty}
{1+\|n^k\|_\infty}
\le {\rm tol}_{\rm N}.
\]
For the one-dimensional numerical experiments, we take
\[
{\rm tol}_{\rm N}=10^{-10}.
\]
For the two-dimensional simulations, the same stopping criterion is used,
with a tolerance chosen according to the mesh resolution.

Several safeguards are used in the implementation. The initial guess is
chosen as
\[
p_i^{[0]}=\max\{p_i^k,p_{\min}\},
\]
where \(p_{\min}>0\) is a small cutoff. This avoids evaluating
\(p_i^{1/\gamma-1}\) at zero in the Jacobian matrix. The residual
\eqref{eq:app-newton-residual}, however, is always evaluated from the
original nonlinear equation. Moreover, when \(|p_i^k-p_H|\) is below a
prescribed threshold, the reaction mobility is evaluated by its limiting
value
\[
M_i^k=-n_i^kG'(p_H),
\]
in agreement with the definition of the scheme.

In one space dimension, the linear Newton system is solved by a direct
tridiagonal solver. In two space dimensions, the same procedure leads to
a sparse matrix with the standard five-point structure, and the Newton
correction is computed by a sparse linear solver. Since the mobility
coefficients are frozen at time level \(t_k\), only the diagonal
nonlinear contribution in \eqref{eq:app-newton-jac-diag} changes during
the Newton iteration.















